theorem
Th18: ((seq1 is  bounded & seq2 is  bounded) implies ( seq1 + seq2 ) is  bounded)
proof
assume that
A1: seq1 is  bounded
and
A2: seq2 is  bounded;
consider M2 such that A3: M2 > ( 0 ) and A4: (for n holds ||. ( seq2 . n ) .|| <= M2) by A2,CKB21:def 1;
consider M1 such that A5: M1 > ( 0 ) and A6: (for n holds ||. ( seq1 . n ) .|| <= M1) by A1,CKB21:def 1;
now
let n;
||. ( ( seq1 + seq2 ) . n ) .|| = ||. ( ( seq1 . n ) + ( seq2 . n ) ) .|| by NORMSP_1:def 2;
then A7: ||. ( ( seq1 + seq2 ) . n ) .|| <= ( ||. ( seq1 . n ) .|| + ||. ( seq2 . n ) .|| ) by BHSP_1:30;
(||. ( seq1 . n ) .|| <= M1 & ||. ( seq2 . n ) .|| <= M2) by A6,A4;
then ( ||. ( seq1 . n ) .|| + ||. ( seq2 . n ) .|| ) <= ( M1 + M2 ) by XREAL_1:7;
hence ||. ( ( seq1 + seq2 ) . n ) .|| <= ( M1 + M2 ) by A7,XXREAL_0:2;
end;
hence thesis by A5,A3,CKB21:def 1;
end;
